The better world is already here
COPENHAGEN – For centuries, optimists and pessimists have discussed the state of the world.
Pessimists see a world where more people mean less food, where increasing resource needs lead to plundering and war, and where the growing production capacity of recent decades brings more pollution and global warming in its wake.
One of the holy texts of the current generation of pessimists, The Limits to Growth, still influences the environmental movement today.
Optimists, on the other hand, claim that everything is getting better – human health, living standards, environmental quality, and so on.
Von ihren Gegnern werden sie als „Ökonomen des Überflusses“ gesehen, die dem Markt vertrauen, der angeblich alle Probleme löst.
Aber statt Tatsachen und Geschichten herauszupicken, die in eine große Erzählung von Niedergang oder Fortschritt passen, sollten wir versuchen, alle Bereiche der menschlichen Existenz zu vergleichen, um zu sehen, ob die Welt wirklich besser oder schlechter wird.
Genau dies habe ich gemeinsam mit 21 weltweit führenden Ökonomen dadurch zu erreichen versucht, dass wir eine Wertungsliste der letzten 150 Jahre entwickelten.
In zehn Bereichen – darunter Gesundheit, Ausbildung, Krieg, Geschlechterverhältnis, Luftverschmutzung, Klimaveränderung und Biodiversität – haben die Ökonomen alle dieselbe Frage beantwortet: Wie hoch waren die relativen Kosten dieses Problems in jedem Jahr von 1900 bis 2013, einschließlich Prognosen bis 2050.
Anhand klassischer ökonomischer Bewertungen aller Faktoren von Todesopfern, Gesundheitsschäden und Analphabetentum über die Zerstörung von Feuchtgebieten bis hin zu höherem Hurrikan-Risiko durch globale Erwärmung zeigen die Ökonomen die Kosten jedes einzelnen Problems auf.
To assess the magnitude of the problem, it is compared with the total resources available for its solution.
This makes the size of the problem clear as a percentage of GDP.
And the trends since 1900 are sometimes surprising.
Let's consider gender inequality.
In essence, we had excluded almost half of the world's population from production at that time.
1900 only 15% of the workforce worldwide was female.
What are the losses that arose from this small proportion?
Even if we consider the higher costs of educating women and that someone has to do unpaid household work, the losses amounted to at least 17% of world GDP in 1900.
Today, with a higher female labor force participation and lower income disparities, the loss is 7% – and is likely to fall to 4% by 2050.
It will likely be surprising that climate change from 1900 to 2025 is expected to result in a growing net benefit – rising up to 1.5% of GDP annually.
This lies in the different effects of global warming. If it only occurs moderately, the benefit prevails.
On one hand, higher CO2 entries were a blessing for agriculture, as the gas acts as a fertilizer. This is the greatest positive effect amounting to 0.8% of GDP.
Similarly, moderate warming prevents more deaths from cold than it causes additional deaths from heat.
It also reduces heating needs more significantly than it creates new cooling needs, corresponding to a benefit of about 0.4% of GDP.
On the other hand, warming leads to water shortages, which cost around 0.2% of GDP, and has a negative impact on ecosystems like wetlands, resulting in a loss of approximately 0.1%.
However, as temperatures continue to rise, costs increase and advantages decrease, dramatically reducing the net benefit.
After 2070, global warming will cause net costs worldwide, justifying cost-effective climate protection today and in the coming decades.
However, the ranking also shows that the world's biggest environmental problem is indoor air pollution in homes, which puts things into perspective.
Today, more than three million people die each year from indoor air pollution caused by harmful emissions from cooking and heating, which amounts to a loss of 3% of global GDP.
But in 1900, these costs equaled 19% of GDP, and it is expected that they will fall to 1% by 2050.
The health indicators have improved the most worldwide.
Until the late 18th century, human life expectancy changed hardly at all.
The gain since 1900 cannot be overstated: At that time, the global life expectancy was 32 years, and today it is 69 years (and likely to be 76 years in 2050).
The biggest factor was the reduction in child mortality.
For example, in 1970 only 5% of infants were vaccinated against measles, tetanus, whooping cough, diphtheria, and polio.
In the year 2000, it was 85%, which led to the rescue of three million lives every year – more than would have been saved by world peace in the entire 20th century.
This success has many parents.
The Gates Foundation and the GAVI Alliance have spent more than 2.5 billion USD on vaccines and promised another 10 billion.
Through the efforts of the Rotary Club, the World Health Organization, and many others, the cases of polio since 1979 have been reduced by 99%.
In economic terms, the costs of worse health at the beginning of the 20th century were astonishingly 32% of the global GDP.
They have declined to about 11% and will halve again by 2050.
Even if the optimists are not entirely correct in every point (the loss of biodiversity in the twentieth century likely costs about 1% of GDP annually, and in some places much more), the overall picture is clear.
The majority of the studied topics show improvements of 5-20% of GDP.
And the general trend is even more pronounced.
Relative to the global problems that can be addressed with available resources, they have dramatically declined.
Naturally, this does not mean that there are no problems anymore.
Even though they have become smaller in areas such as health, education, malnutrition, air pollution, gender inequality, and trade, they are still significant.
But realists should slowly get used to the idea that the world has improved considerably.
Furthermore, the ranking shows us where the challenges for a better 2050 lie.
We should not set our sights on the future based on the most horrific stories or loudest interest groups, but rather on objective assessments of the areas where we can achieve the greatest improvements.
